<TITLE> CPB to protest price hikes, rising violence on Sept 5 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 29 (bdnews24.com)  Communist Party of Bangladesh has declared countrywide demonstrations on Sept 5 protesting current price hikes, the rise in violent crimes and recent gas exploration agreements with foreign companies. CPB, in a statement released on Saturday, also demanded trial of a grenade attack on a CPB procession at Paltan in Dhaka on Jan 20 2001. The party called too for a 'mass distribution system' through fair-price shops. CPB president Manjurul Ahsan Khan and general secretary Mujahidul Islam Selim has asked all party leaders and members to join the programme. Meanwhile, BNP has also announced a Sept 6-7 protest programme against price hikes and "deteriorating law and order" And a citizens' pressure group  calling itself the 'national committee to protect oil, gas, mineral resources, power and ports'  has also announced a demonstration, including a planned seige of Petrobangla's head office on Sept 2, in protest against the government's decision last week to award gas exploration rights in three sea blocks in the Bay of Bengal to two foreign companies. bdnew
